6b-88ef-b420cabd4d4c--2018-0731_mizuba-tea-co_japanese-matcha-chasen_1x1_julia-gartland_123.jpg, https://images.food52.com/exyzJyNxkjUU7AtYroQAkHvq9pQ=/750x750/7c04328d-14c2-456b-88ef-b420cabd4d4c--2018-0731_mizuba-tea-co_japanese-matcha-chasen_1x1_julia-gartland_123.jpg 2x\" alt=\"\" width=\"964\" height=\"964\" data-expand=\"750\" data-srcset=\"https://images.food52.com/WXLbxO_zm3UFHAcMETNzxrSykFo=/375x375/7c04328d-14c2-456b-88ef-b420cabd4d4c--2018-0731_mizuba-tea-co_japanese-matcha-chasen_1x1_julia-gartland_123.jpg, https://images.food52.com/exyzJyNxkjUU7AtYroQAkHvq9pQ=/750x750/7c04328d-14c2-456b-88ef-b420cabd4d4c--2018-0731_mizuba-tea-co_japanese-matcha-chasen_1x1_julia-gartland_123.jpg 2x\"/\u003e\u003c/picture\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\n      \u003cfigcaption\u003e\n\n          \u003cspan\u003ePhoto by Julia Gartland\u003c/span\u003e\n      \u003c/figcaption\u003e\n  \u003c/figure\u003e\n\n              \u003ch2\u003eWhat Is Matcha?\u003c/h2\u003e\n              \u003cp\u003eMatcha is a type of finely ground green tea made from specially grown and processed tea leaves. Unlike traditional green tea (which steeps leaves in a bag), you\u0026#39;re consuming the whole leaf—which means you’re also getting more antioxidants, caffeine, and chlorophyll.\u003c/p\u003e\n              \u003cp\u003eThere are two main types of matcha you’ll find in stores:\u003c/p\u003e\n              \u003ch3\u003eCeremonial vs. Culinary Matcha\u003c/h3\u003e\n              \u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCeremonial grade\u003c/strong\u003e is made with younger, higher-quality leaves and has a naturally sweet, smooth flavor. It’s intended to be whisked with hot water and enjoyed on its own. You’ll also notice it\u0026#39;s more of a bright green color.\u003c/p\u003e\n              \u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCulinary grade\u003c/strong\u003e is slightly more bitter and a bit less vibrant in color—it’s perfect for mixing into smoothies, baking, cooking, or sweetened drinks (also because it’s cheaper).\u003c/p\u003e\n              \n              \u003cp\u003eMatcha isn’t just for tea. It’s incredibly versatile, which is why we’ve seen it pop up in everything from brownies to steak rubs. Depending on the grade, here’s how to use it:\u003c/p\u003e\n              \u003cp\u003e• \u003cstrong\u003eIn baking\u003c/strong\u003e: Add culinary matcha to cookies, cakes, or muffins for a subtle green tea flavor and a gorgeous hue.\u003c/p\u003e\n              \u003cp\u003e• \u003cstrong\u003eIn drinks\u003c/strong\u003e: Make iced matcha lattes, matcha lemonades, or even matcha-espresso combos.\u003c/p\u003e\n              \u003cp\u003e• \u003cstrong\u003eIn savory recipes\u003c/strong\u003e: Yes, it can work! Think matcha spice rubs or tahini dressings with a hint of earthiness.\u003c/p\u003e\n              \n\n  \u003cfigure\u003e\n    \u003cdiv\u003e\n      \u003ca href=\"https://www.pinterest.com/pin/create/button\" data-pin-do=\"buttonPin\" data-pin-media=\"\" data-pin-custom=\"true\" data-ga-event=\"inPageInteraction\" data-ga-event-action=\"Pinterest Share\" data-ga-event-label=\"Article Body Image\" data-ga-destination-url=\"none\"\u003e\n        \u003csvg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" viewBox=\"0 0 16.9 20.8\"\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M16.8 6.3C16.5 3.2 13.6.4 10.1.1 4.8-.5.1 2.7 0 7.9c0 2.4.8 4 2.9 4.8 1.5-1.5-.3-2.4-.5-4C2 4.3 7.1.1 11.7 2.9c3.2 1.9 2.6 9.9-1.2 10.7-.8.1-1.8-.1-2.1-.5-1.9-1.8 1.5-4.8.4-7.3-.9-2.1-3.6-.4-3.9 1.5-.2 1 .3 2 .3 2.9 0 2.1-1.3 5-1.7 7.1-.2.9-.3 2.6-.1 3.4h1.5c1-1.6 1.6-4.1 2.1-6.3.3-.2.5.4.7.6 1.8 1.4 5 .6 6.4-.7 2.1-1.7 3-5.2 2.7-8\" fill=\"currentColor\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e\n      \u003c/a\u003e\n\n      \u003cdiv\u003e\u003cpicture\u003e\u003csource srcset=\"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\" media=\"(min-width: 1400px)\" type=\"image/webp\" data-srcset=\"https://images.food52.com/RB2OrZI46zKSfhop4LFUbDWenFg=/778x778/filters:format(webp